So you are correct, with 3.x.x the way navigation works has changed. Moving from one screen to another does not actually unmount the previous one. This is because with 3.x.x the navigation stack uses the native behaviour which preserves the state of the previous screen when pushing a route. 

React navigation instead fires events for willBlur, willFocus, didBlur and didFocus which can be used to detect when a user enters and exits a screen. You can take a look at the API spec for more details on the react navigation [documentation][1]


  [1]: https://reactnavigation.org/docs/en/3.x/navigation-prop.html#addlistener-subscribe-to-updates-to-navigation-lifecycle &quot;here&quot;

